[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per active member per month (depends on engagement frequency, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, multi-system integration count, and care-management-handoff overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria is 67. Maria has type 2 diabetes that has been in moderate control for about a decade, hypertension that has been in good control on a small handful of medications for longer, mild chronic kidney disease, osteoarthritis in both knees, an echocardiogram from two years ago that flagged some changes her cardiologist wanted to recheck this year, and a screening colonoscopy that her primary care physician noted at her last annual visit was overdue. Maria's primary care physician is a busy internist at a large multispecialty group; her endocrinologist is at a different group across town that is on the same hospital system but a different medical record; her cardiologist is at the academic medical center because that is where the heart-failure specialist she saw briefly two years ago practices; her nephrologist is at the academic medical center too but in a different building and a different department; her orthopedist is independent and shares records with the multispecialty group through a referral relationship that requires fax at least once per encounter; her gastroenterologist (who will do the colonoscopy when it eventually gets scheduled) is at the multispecialty group; her physical therapist (for the knees) is at a chain that does not share records with any of them; her pharmacist is at the regional grocery-store chain; her case manager (assigned by her Medicare Advantage plan in October because her plan's risk model flagged her) is employed by the plan and works from a call center she has never visited.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria has, in the last six weeks: had her annual physical with her primary care physician, who noted the colonoscopy gap, ordered a basic metabolic panel and a hemoglobin A1c and a microalbumin and a lipid panel, refilled her metformin and her lisinopril, suggested but did not formally place a referral to the cardiologist for the echocardiogram recheck, suggested she ask the orthopedist about a knee injection given the worsening pain, and asked her to follow up in six weeks; gone to the lab and had her blood drawn; received a portal message saying her A1c was 7.4 (up from 6.9 last time) and her microalbumin was elevated and her primary care physician wanted her to "discuss with endocrinology and consider increasing the metformin or adding a second agent"; called the endocrinologist's office and gotten a voicemail and not heard back for ten days; called again and gotten an appointment scheduled for nine weeks from now; had the orthopedist's office call her about scheduling the knee injection but declined because she could not figure out what her copay would be; received an automated text from the cardiologist's office saying she had a referral on file and asking her to call to schedule, but the referral was for the wrong cardiologist (her old one, from the time she had insurance through her late husband's plan, who is not currently in network); received a paper letter from the gastroenterologist's office saying her colonoscopy was on file but that the prep instructions would arrive by mail two weeks before the procedure (the procedure had not been scheduled); and missed two calls from her Medicare Advantage plan's case manager who was trying to introduce herself.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria has not had her echocardiogram recheck. Maria has not seen the endocrinologist. Maria has not had the colonoscopy. Maria has not had the knee injection. Maria has not started any second diabetes agent. Maria has not connected with her case manager. Maria's A1c is sitting at 7.4 with concerning microalbumin, and Maria has accumulated, in six weeks, about fourteen open care-coordination items between her seven providers, none of which are tracked in any single system, none of which are visible to any single human, and most of which Maria is, in practice, the case manager for.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria is a competent, articulate, college-educated woman who managed her late husband's far more complex care for the last eight years of his life. Maria is also tired, has cognitive load from being a primary caregiver to her adult son who has a developmental disability, has a flip phone she got because the smartphone gave her headaches and the apps confused her, does not use a patient portal because she could never remember which of three portals went with which provider, and is not, in any meaningful sense, going to be the case manager for fourteen open items across seven providers using paper, voicemail, and her own memory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the care-coordination problem, and Maria is not an unusual case. The American healthcare system, as currently structured, expects patients with chronic conditions to navigate a fragmented network of independently-operating providers, each with their own scheduling system, their own portal, their own billing department, their own referral process, their own communication preferences, their own electronic medical record (or, often, paper), and their own conception of who is responsible for what. The expectation is wildly unrealistic for the population most affected. Older adults with multiple chronic conditions, the population that needs care coordination most, are also the population least equipped to perform the coordination labor the system implicitly demands of them. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on care fragmentation, multimorbidity, and the patient as default coordinator is extensive; specific findings vary by population and system context -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The professionals who know this best are case managers, care coordinators, social workers, and patient navigators. These are the humans whose actual job is to do the work the system implicitly outsources to patients: track open care items across providers, follow up on referrals, confirm appointment scheduling, verify lab and imaging completion, reconcile medication lists across pharmacies, coordinate with social services for transportation and food and housing concerns, advocate with insurance for prior authorizations and appeals, and bridge between providers who do not naturally communicate. The work is difficult, valuable, and chronically under-resourced. The case-management workforce in the U.S. is not large enough to cover the population that needs it. Most patients who would benefit from care coordination do not get it, because the supply does not exist; the patients who do get it tend to be the ones whose conditions are severe enough or whose plans are generous enough or whose advocates are noisy enough to make the case for the limited human resource. <!-- TODO: verify; the case-management workforce supply, the proportion of multimorbid patients receiving formal care management, and the variation in coverage by payer type are documented in workforce and population-health literature; specific figures vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generations of digital tools tried to address this in a few ways. The first wave was patient portals, which assumed the patient would log in to each provider's portal and read the messages and click the links to schedule appointments and follow up on results. Patient-portal adoption among multimorbid older adults has been modest, with substantial digital-divide concerns, and even among adopters the portals do not solve coordination across providers because each portal is provider-specific. <!-- TODO: verify; patient-portal adoption rates and the disparities by age, education, race, ethnicity, language, and income are documented in HHS, ONC, and academic literature; specific figures vary by year and population --> The second wave was care-management software for case managers and care coordinators, which made the case-manager workflow more efficient but did not extend the supply of case managers and did not, by itself, improve the patient experience meaningfully. The third wave was reminder and outreach systems (text-message reminders for appointments, gap-in-care outreach campaigns, refill reminders), which closed some gaps and did not solve the structural fragmentation. The fourth wave, which is where this recipe lives, is conversational AI that, deployed with careful institutional governance and integrated with the underlying scheduling, referral, eligibility, EHR, and care-management systems, can take on much of the cross-provider coordination labor on behalf of the patient with human care-management backup for the cases that need it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about building, carefully, a care coordination assistant that Maria could use, that does not require her to install an app, that meets her where she is (text message, phone call, web, or in-person at the multispecialty group's kiosk), that knows about her seven providers and her open referrals and her overdue colonoscopy and her not-yet-scheduled echocardiogram and her elevated A1c and her case manager's voicemails, and that can do what a competent case manager would do for her if a competent case manager were available: track the open items, surface the next-best action, schedule the appointments, confirm the referrals, verify the eligibility, message the providers, escalate to a human when the situation calls for it, and stay with Maria across the months it takes to work through the list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the assistant that supports patients with care-coordination needs across multiple providers, multiple care-management touchpoints, multiple insurance interactions, and multiple service categories (clinical, social, behavioral). It tracks open care items, surfaces next-best actions, executes coordination tasks where automation is appropriate (scheduling, referral confirmation, eligibility check, prior-authorization status), and escalates to human care managers for the cases that need a human.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a primary care provider. It does not make medical decisions, does not adjust treatments, does not diagnose, does not interpret labs beyond reading what the provider already wrote. The clinical decisions belong to the patient's clinicians.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a case manager. It is a tool that extends the case-management workforce. The licensed-case-manager-or-care-coordinator workforce is the safety architecture; the bot does the routine coordination labor and routes to a human for everything else. Deploying this without sufficient case-management capacity is a deployment-readiness gap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a closed-loop guarantee. The bot can confirm that a referral was placed, that an appointment was scheduled, that a prescription was sent, but it cannot guarantee that the patient went to the appointment or that the cardiologist looked at the referral or that the prior authorization was granted. It tracks the loops, surfaces the open ones, and persistently nudges (without being annoying) until they close.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a portal replacement. It is a conversational layer over the systems the institution already operates: the EHR, the scheduling system, the referral system, the eligibility system, the care-management system, the pharmacy system. The bot reads from and writes to these systems with appropriate authorization. The systems remain the source of truth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-size-fits-all product. The needs of a high-acuity, dually-eligible, social-determinant-rich patient are meaningfully different from the needs of a moderately-engaged, commercially-insured patient with two chronic conditions. The bot's behavior, scope, and escalation thresholds are tuned per cohort with care-management-leadership input.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters. The integration work is multi-quarter, the policy work is multi-quarter, the workforce coordination work is multi-quarter, and the outcome demonstration is multi-year. Institutions building this expecting a fast time-to-value are usually disappointed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the bot's value is not in the cleverness of any single response. The value is in three places: the persistence with which the bot tracks open coordination items across providers (the bot does not forget about Maria's overdue colonoscopy at week three, week six, or week twelve), the consistency with which it surfaces the next-best action at the right moment (the bot reaches out about the echocardiogram referral when Maria's calendar is open and the cardiologist's office is staffed, not at 2 AM), and the warm-handoff infrastructure that gets the patient to a human case manager in the cases that need one. A bot evaluated on per-conversation engagement metrics will be optimized for the wrong thing. A bot evaluated on care-gap-closure rate, referral-completion rate, appointment-scheduling success rate, prior-authorization-resolution rate, patient-experience scores, and (eventually) clinical-outcome trajectories is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[K
