Purpose: Append Technology section

[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Conversational Care Coordination Grounded In Multi-System Integration, Persistent Task State, and Warm Handoff
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Digital Tools, and Why The Latest Attempts Are Different
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical and operational workflow, has been a human-and-paper-and-fax problem for almost all of its history. The reason is structural. Care coordination is not a single task; it is a sequence of dozens of small, mostly-routine, mostly-process tasks distributed across many independent organizations, each with its own data model, scheduling system, communication channel, billing department, and operational tempo. The tasks themselves are tractable individually. The fragmentation is the problem. A case manager doing care coordination spends a substantial fraction of their day on phone calls, fax forms, portal logins, voicemail follow-up, email threads, and waiting for callbacks. The cognitive load is in tracking many open items across many systems, none of which talk to each other natively. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on case-manager workload, the time spent on coordination versus direct patient care, and the proportion of administrative friction is documented in nursing and care-management literature; specific findings vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Digital tools have, for most of their history, been able to address pieces of this and not the whole. EHRs solve within-organization continuity but not cross-organization. Health information exchanges solve some cross-organization data flow but not the workflow. Patient portals offload some communication tasks to patients but assume patient capacity that is often absent. Care-management software (the case-manager-facing tools) makes the human case manager more efficient without changing the supply. None of these tools, individually, addresses the structural problem of "Maria has fourteen open coordination items across seven providers, no human is tracking them all, and the system implicitly expects Maria to."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape, again, is large language models that can carry on a coherent, task-oriented, multi-turn conversation while invoking tools to read from and write to the underlying systems. A conversational care-coordination assistant, deployed with careful integration into the institution's scheduling, referral, eligibility, pharmacy, EHR, care-management, and social-services systems, can do much of the work that a case manager would do if one were available: track open items, surface the next-best action, schedule appointments, confirm referrals, verify eligibility, route prior-authorization questions, message providers, log social-determinant concerns, and escalate to a human case manager when the situation calls for one. The LLM is not the case manager. The LLM is, in the right product design, a tool that extends the reach of the case-management workforce by handling the routine coordination labor at scale and routing the human-judgment work to a human.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "patient logs into seven portals to coordinate their care" to "patient has one conversational interface that reads and writes across seven systems on their behalf, with a human backstop." The bot's value is concentrated in three places: persistent tracking of open coordination items (the bot does not forget; the bot does not get distracted by another patient; the bot does not go on vacation), low-friction patient interaction (the patient texts in plain language; the bot translates to and from the institution's structured systems), and operational reach extension (the bot serves a population the licensed-case-manager workforce alone could not reach).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on what care-coordination AI is and is not, because the category overlaps with several adjacent ones. The narrow end of the scope is closed-loop coordination on a defined set of tasks (referral confirmation, appointment scheduling, prior-auth status, refill follow-up, gap-in-care outreach). The broader end of the scope is longitudinal companion-style support for complex, multi-condition patients with social-determinant needs. This recipe targets the broader end, with the understanding that not every deployment will start there. Most institutions phase the deployment: launch with a narrow set of high-value coordination tasks, expand scope as the integrations mature and the operational confidence grows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant, as designed in this recipe, is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active conditions, current medications, care team, open coordination items, recent encounters, scheduled appointments, pending referrals, recent labs, social-determinant flags, plan benefits, conversation history, stated patient preferences), access to a structured library of patient-facing content for common coordination scenarios (appointment-prep instructions, referral explanations, prior-auth navigation tips, eligibility explanations, transportation-resource information, financial-assistance information), and a careful set of tools for reading and writing to the underlying institutional systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes, often initiated by the bot per a tracked open item ("I see your colonoscopy hasn't been scheduled yet; would you like me to help with that?"), sometimes initiated by the patient ("I got a letter about prep instructions and I'm confused"), sometimes triggered by an external event (a referral was placed, a lab result arrived, an appointment was rescheduled, a prior-authorization decision came back), sometimes triggered by a care-team event (the case manager flags a patient for outreach).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Onboarding and consent.** The patient is enrolled by their care team, by their plan's care-management program, or self-enrolls through the institution's app or portal, with documented consent specific to care-coordination AI interaction. The first conversation does the disclosure work: the bot identifies itself as a chat tool and not a person, describes what it does (track care-coordination items, schedule appointments, follow up on referrals, surface eligibility and benefits information, escalate to a human case manager when needed), describes what it does not do (make medical decisions, adjust treatments, diagnose, replace the care team), names the human-case-manager availability, and describes the privacy posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Open-item tracking and next-best-action surfacing.** The bot maintains a persistent list of open coordination items per patient, sourced from EHR data, scheduling-system data, referral-system data, eligibility data, pharmacy data, lab-result data, care-plan data, and care-management-team flags. Each item has a state (open, in-progress, blocked, completed, abandoned), an owner (patient, bot, case manager, provider), an expected next action, an expected next-action timeframe, and a history of attempts. The bot uses the open-item list to drive proactive outreach (gentle, timely, channel-appropriate) and to ground reactive conversations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Appointment scheduling and rescheduling.** Where the institution's scheduling system permits API-based scheduling, the bot can schedule, reschedule, or cancel appointments on the patient's behalf, taking into account the patient's stated preferences (preferred time of day, preferred day of week, transportation constraints, accompaniment needs), the provider's available slots, and the appointment-type-specific requirements (lab-fasting, imaging prep, prior-auth status). The bot does not invent appointments; the bot calls the scheduling system and reflects the response.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Referral tracking and confirmation.** The bot tracks open referrals from origination through completion: was the referral placed in the EHR, was it received by the receiving provider, was the patient contacted to schedule, was the appointment scheduled, did the patient attend, was the consultation note returned. The bot can identify stalled referrals and either nudge the patient (where patient action is needed) or escalate to the case manager (where institutional action is needed).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Lab and imaging completion tracking.** The bot tracks ordered labs and imaging from order through result-receipt-and-acknowledgment. The bot can remind the patient of unfilled lab orders, can answer prep questions for upcoming imaging, and can route patient questions about results to the ordering provider (the bot does not interpret results clinically).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Eligibility and benefits navigation.** The bot retrieves real-time eligibility information from the patient's plan and answers patient questions about coverage, copays, deductibles, in-network status, prior-authorization requirements, and coordination of benefits. The bot does not give legally-binding coverage determinations; the bot provides plan-data-grounded answers with explicit disclaimers and routes uncertain cases to plan benefits counselors. (See Recipe 11.5 for the deep dive on this pattern; the care coordination assistant inherits much of that recipe's machinery.)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior-authorization status tracking.** The bot tracks open prior authorizations from submission through decision, can read decision letters when they post to the EHR or plan portal, and can explain the decision to the patient (approval, denial, request for additional information, peer-to-peer required). The bot escalates denial-and-appeal cases to the case manager.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prescription refill coordination.** The bot tracks refill status across the patient's pharmacies, can submit refill requests where the institution's pharmacy integration permits, and can resolve simple refill questions (refills remaining, generic substitution availability, formulary status). The bot escalates clinical refill questions (dose change requests, controlled-substance refills, drug-interaction concerns) to the prescribing provider.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Transition-of-care coordination.** When the patient is discharged from a hospital or skilled-nursing stay, the bot can support the transition: confirm the discharge summary went to the patient's primary care physician, confirm the discharge-medication list reconciled, confirm the post-discharge appointment is scheduled, surface the patient's discharge instructions in plain language, and nudge if the post-discharge appointment is missed. The bot does not own the transition; the post-discharge clinical-handoff team owns it. The bot is the patient's coordination companion during the window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants-of-health screening and routing.** The bot can administer (with care-team review) brief social-determinants screeners (food insecurity, housing instability, transportation barriers, financial hardship), can connect patients with appropriate resources (community-based organizations, plan-funded benefits, institutional financial-assistance programs), and can flag positive screens to the care-management team for human follow-up. The bot does not make legally-binding eligibility determinations for social-services programs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team communication facilitation.** The bot can compose patient-side messages to the care team (in the patient's voice, with the patient's review and approval), can route incoming care-team messages with appropriate clarifying questions, and can support care-team-initiated patient outreach (e.g., the case manager asks the bot to deliver a specific reminder).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Crisis and emergency screening.** The bot screens every patient utterance for emergency indicators (acute symptoms suggesting myocardial infarction, stroke, severe shortness of breath, severe pain, suicidal crisis), and routes to 911, the institution's crisis line, or 988 as appropriate. The crisis screening from Recipe 11.6 (triage bot) and Recipe 11.8 (mental health support bot) carries forward.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Longitudinal relationship maintenance.** The bot maintains conversation history and stated patient preferences across months and years. The bot can acknowledge prior context ("last month you mentioned the transportation issue with the cardiology appointment; how is that going?") in ways that support continuity without simulating friendship. The bot is, structurally, a tool that knows the patient's care-coordination history, not a person who remembers them affectionately.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Warm handoff to human case managers.** The bot escalates to a human case manager when the situation calls for it: any uncertain clinical question, any social-determinant crisis, any prior-authorization denial requiring appeal, any insurance dispute, any patient-experience concern (the patient is frustrated, the bot is being unhelpful), any sustained pattern of concern (gaps not closing, appointments repeatedly missed, social-determinant deterioration), any patient request for a human. The handoff is warm: full conversation context attached, no patient restart, bridge-and-stay-present pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, prompt it with "you are a helpful care-coordination assistant," and let it engage with patients. This breaks in several specific ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no reliable connection to the institution's systems.** Care coordination is, structurally, work performed against the EHR, the scheduling system, the referral system, the eligibility system, the pharmacy system, the care-management system. A bot without authenticated, audited, transactionally-correct connections to these systems is making things up. The tool surface is not optional; it is the architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no persistent open-item state.** A bot that does not remember Maria's overdue colonoscopy from one conversation to the next is not doing care coordination. The longitudinal open-item store is the architectural primitive, and it lives in a database the institution owns, not in the model's context window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to act and when to wait.** Care coordination is heavy on timing: the cardiologist's office is staffed weekdays 8 AM to 5 PM in a specific time zone; the prior-authorization decision is expected within seven business days; the colonoscopy prep instructions are sent two weeks before the procedure; the post-discharge appointment is recommended within seven days. The orchestration logic that says "follow up on this on day three after the previous attempt, but only during business hours, and only via the channel the patient prefers, and not during the patient's stated quiet hours" is encoded in the bot's task scheduler, not in the LLM's emergent behavior.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to invoke which integration.** Calling the wrong API, calling the right API with wrong arguments, or skipping a required step (like checking eligibility before scheduling a specialist appointment that requires prior auth) all produce specific operational failures. The Bedrock Agents tool surface, with explicit OpenAPI schemas and per-tool input validation, encapsulates each capability deterministically.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents appointment slots, referral statuses, and benefit details when grounded retrieval is missing.** A bot that hallucinates "your appointment is confirmed for Tuesday at 2 PM" when no such appointment exists is failing at the only thing it is supposed to do. Every patient-facing claim about a system-of-record fact (appointment, referral, lab result, medication, benefit) is grounded in a retrieved record from the system of record, with the source preserved in the audit trail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of what to escalate.** A patient saying "I've been having chest pain for the last hour" is not a care-coordination question; it is an emergency. A patient saying "my sister told me my mother is being abused at her care facility" is a mandatory-reporting trigger, not a care-coordination question. A patient saying "the prior auth was denied and the medication is $700 a month and I can't pay" is a case-manager escalation, not a self-serve answer. The escalation logic is encoded explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of authorization scope.** The bot can read and write certain things on the patient's behalf and not others. The bot can schedule a primary-care follow-up but cannot schedule a procedure that requires informed-consent counseling. The bot can submit a refill request but cannot order a controlled substance. The bot can compose a message to the care team but cannot send a message to the prescribing provider asking for a dose change. The authorization-scope rules are institutional policy, encoded in the tool layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications around eligibility and benefits.** Statements about insurance coverage are subject to ERISA, ACA, and state-specific regulations. Saying "your insurance covers this" when it does not is a statement with real consequences. The eligibility-and-benefits machinery from Recipe 11.5 (with its explicit disclaimers, plan-data-grounded answers, and routing to benefits counselors for uncertain cases) is part of the architectural inheritance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of patient capacity.** A bot that responds to Maria with the same complexity, vocabulary, and pace as it responds to a 28-year-old health-IT engineer is mis-serving Maria. The patient-capacity awareness (reading level, language, channel preferences, accessibility needs, cognitive load) is a deliberate design choice, encoded in the patient-preferences store and reflected in the response composition.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of social-determinant complexity.** A patient who says "I can't make the appointment because I don't have a ride" needs a transportation resource, not a stern reminder about the importance of attendance. The social-determinant-of-health machinery (screeners, resource libraries, community-based-organization referrals, plan-funded transportation benefits) is part of the bot's tool surface, not an afterthought.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of care-team relationships.** The patient's primary care physician is the medical home; the patient's case manager is the care-coordination home; the patient's specialists are consultants; the patient's pharmacist is a specific kind of resource. The bot's awareness of these relationships, and its respect for who owns what kind of decision, is encoded in the system prompt and reinforced by the output safety pass.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to end an interaction.** A bot that ends a conversation while Maria is in the middle of explaining a confusion erodes trust. A bot that continues a conversation indefinitely when Maria has logistical things to do is mis-serving her. The conversation-ending heuristics are reviewed by patient-experience and care-management leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Care Coordination Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding, behavior-change-stage tracking, crisis-pathway architecture, warm-handoff infrastructure. The care coordination assistant adds six structural commitments those recipes did not have at this depth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system integration as architectural primitive, not feature.** The bot is, in operational terms, a coordination layer over the institution's EHR, scheduling, referral, eligibility, pharmacy, care-management, and social-services systems. Each integration is contract-managed, idempotent on writes, audited on every call, and degraded gracefully when upstream is unavailable. The integration surface is the architecture; the LLM is the orchestration glue.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Persistent open-item state with care-team ownership.** The open coordination items per patient are tracked in a durable store that the bot, the patient, the care team, and the case manager all have appropriate views into. The state is the source of truth; the LLM does not invent items, does not lose items, does not move items to "done" without evidence. The care team can audit, edit, add, and close items.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Proactive outreach scheduling with tempo discipline.** The bot does not just respond to patients; it reaches out on the patient's open items, with timing calibrated to the patient's stated preferences, the institution's quiet-hours policies, and the recipient's likelihood of engaging at a given time. The outreach scheduler is its own subsystem, with per-cohort tempo policies reviewed by patient-experience leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational metric integration with care-management workforce.** The bot's metrics (engagement rate, gap-closure rate, referral-completion rate, scheduling-success rate, patient-experience scores, escalation-completion rate) feed into the care-management leadership's operational dashboards. The bot does not exist independently of the case-management workforce; it is part of the workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-running episodic context with cohort calibration.** Care coordination is months-to-years work, not days-to-weeks work. The conversation history, open-item history, escalation history, and outcome history accumulate over time and are summarized for the LLM's context window with cohort-specific summarization policies (a high-acuity dually-eligible patient's summary structure differs from a moderately-engaged commercially-insured patient's).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Explicit care-team-versus-bot scope clarity.** The bot is not the case manager. The bot is a tool that extends the case manager. The bot's scope (what it can do, what it routes, what it escalates) is institutionally specified and reviewed by care-management leadership. The patient is told, on every relevant occasion, what the bot is and is not. The case manager retains ownership of the patient's care-coordination plan.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Integration depth is the dominant cost driver, and most organizations underestimate it.** Connecting the bot to the EHR, the scheduling system, the referral system, the eligibility system, the pharmacy system, the care-management system, and the social-services systems is the bulk of the engineering work. Each integration has its own contract, its own authorization model, its own latency profile, its own failure modes, its own change-management cadence. The institutional integration team is the critical path; the LLM work is comparatively cheap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-segment heterogeneity drives feature complexity.** The needs of a high-acuity dually-eligible Medicare-Medicaid patient are different from the needs of a moderately-engaged commercially-insured patient with two chronic conditions, which are different from the needs of a Medicare Advantage senior with mild cognitive impairment, which are different from the needs of a pregnant adolescent on a Medicaid plan. Most deployments select a primary cohort, design for that cohort, and expand carefully. Designing for "all patients" without segmentation usually produces a bot that serves none of them well.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Channel diversity is non-negotiable for the population that needs care coordination most.** The patients who benefit most from care coordination are disproportionately older, lower-income, lower-digital-fluency, and limited-English-proficient. A bot that operates only in one channel (web chat, say), only in English, only at one reading level, only during business hours, is excluding much of its target population. Multi-channel (SMS, voice, web, in-person kiosk), multilingual, multi-reading-level, and 24/7-with-human-backstop are all expectations, not nice-to-haves.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Engagement attrition has care-coordination-specific drivers.** The patients who need the bot most are also the ones with the most barriers to sustained engagement: cognitive load, social-determinant stressors, distrust of digital tools, distrust of payers, language barriers. Mitigation: relationship-quality engineering; consistent identity-and-tone of the assistant across interactions; easy off-ramp to a human; channel diversity; per-cohort attrition monitoring with care-management-leadership review; willingness to pause outreach when patients ask.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The bot's relationship to the case-management workforce is specifically delicate.** Case managers can perceive the bot as a threat to their role; the bot cannot succeed without their collaboration. The deployment program includes case-management-leadership co-design, case-manager training, explicit role clarity (the bot does the routine; the case manager does the human-judgment work), case-manager-facing dashboards that show what the bot is doing for their patients, and case-manager feedback channels that influence bot behavior. Where this collaboration is weak, the bot underperforms; where it is strong, the bot multiplies the case-management workforce's reach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Referral and appointment-scheduling integrations have specific failure modes.** Referral systems often have data-quality problems (referrals to providers no longer in network, referrals to specialties that don't match the clinical question, referrals with missing prior-auth requirements). Scheduling systems often have business-rule complexity that is hard to extract via API (this provider only schedules new patients on Tuesday afternoons; this appointment type requires a 90-minute slot and the API only exposes 60-minute slots). Mitigation: deep collaboration with the integration owners; tolerance for bot-handled-as-patient-handed-off cases; explicit care-management-team escalation paths.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior-authorization workflows are slow and stateful.** Prior-auth decisions can take days to weeks; the patient may interact with the bot multiple times during the wait; the decision may come back as "approved," "denied," "approved with restrictions," or "more information needed." The bot's prior-auth tracking is its own subsystem, with persistent state, polling logic, decision-letter parsing, and patient-communication policies reviewed by case-management and benefits leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Eligibility and benefits responses have specific compliance considerations.** Statements about insurance coverage are regulated. The bot's responses include explicit disclaimers, are grounded in real-time plan-data retrieval, and route uncertain cases to human plan-benefits counselors. The architectural inheritance from Recipe 11.5 is significant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinant-of-health screening has specific privacy considerations.** Disclosures of food insecurity, housing instability, intimate-partner violence, financial hardship, or substance-use carry sensitivity beyond the average PHI. The bot's data-handling for SDoH disclosures is reviewed by privacy counsel; SDoH disclosures may be governed by 42 CFR Part 2 (for substance use) or state-specific statutes, and may have mandatory-reporting implications (for child abuse, elder abuse, intimate-partner violence). <!-- TODO: verify; SDoH-data privacy considerations include specific statutory protections for substance-use treatment records under 42 CFR Part 2, state-specific protections for intimate-partner-violence disclosures in some states, and mandatory-reporting laws that vary by state and disclosure type -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is multi-year work and is harder to attribute than in single-condition bots.** A care coordination assistant's value shows up in care-gap-closure rates, in referral-completion rates, in appointment-attendance rates, in hospitalization rates, in ED-visit rates, in readmission rates, in patient-experience scores, in case-manager-productivity metrics, and (eventually) in clinical-outcome trajectories. Each of these is influenced by many factors beyond the bot. Mitigation: realistic timeline expectations; careful study design; recognition that observational outcome correlation is suggestive rather than causal; willingness to invest in randomized or quasi-experimental evaluation when the deployment matures.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure has specific dimensions.** The bot is interacting with medically vulnerable patients about medically and financially consequential decisions. A bot that schedules the wrong appointment, that misses a deterioration signal, that gives incorrect benefits information, that fails to escalate a crisis, or that loses an open referral has tangible patient-harm potential. The institutional risk-management team is part of the deployment program; the institutional malpractice carrier may have specific terms for AI-mediated patient interaction; specific cyber-and-AI insurance is increasingly common for this category of deployment. <!-- TODO: verify; the malpractice and AI-liability landscape for patient-facing health AI is rapidly evolving; specific insurance and indemnification practices vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Closed-loop referral management is an active area of investment.** Several large EHR vendors and several specialized care-coordination vendors have shipped closed-loop referral capabilities that track referrals from origination through completion, with workflow integration for both referring and receiving providers. <!-- TODO: verify; the closed-loop-referral category has products from several major EHR and care-coordination vendors; specific feature parity and adoption varies --> Bot-mediated patient-side coordination plugs into these capabilities where they exist.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR-based interoperability is more useful for care coordination than it was three years ago.** US Core profiles, including CarePlan, CareTeam, ServiceRequest, Communication, and Task resources, support care-coordination workflows in ways that earlier FHIR versions did not. <!-- TODO: verify; the US Core FHIR profile set has continued to evolve, with improvements in CarePlan, CareTeam, ServiceRequest, Communication, and Task resource support that matters for care-coordination workflows --> The bot reads from and writes to FHIR where the institution's data infrastructure supports it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA and the Qualified Health Information Network framework support cross-organization data flow.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement, introduced under the 21st Century Cures Act and operationalized in the last few years, supports nationwide health-information exchange in ways that can reduce the cross-organization coordination friction the bot is helping with. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA and the Qualified Health Information Network designation framework continue to be operationalized with specific QHIN designations and information-sharing scope evolving over time --> Care-coordination bots that integrate with the institution's QHIN connections inherit some of this benefit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Health-related social needs (HRSN) screening and interventions are now Medicaid-reimbursable in several states.** The Medicaid 1115 waiver landscape has expanded to include HRSN-related services as reimbursable in some states, changing the operational economics of SDoH-related care coordination. <!-- TODO: verify; the Medicaid 1115 waiver landscape for HRSN services has continued to evolve with specific state-by-state coverage and reimbursement varying --> Bot-mediated SDoH screening and resource navigation feeds into these workflows where they exist.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Conversational interfaces for non-digital-native populations are well-studied.** Voice-first interfaces, SMS-first interfaces, low-literacy text design, and culturally-competent multilingual content are areas with substantial accessibility, UX research, and clinical-research literature. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on conversational-interface design for older adults, low-literacy populations, and limited-English-proficient populations is documented in HCI and health-informatics literature --> Care-coordination bot deployments that draw on this literature do better than ones that don't.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid bot-and-case-manager deployments are the dominant pattern in mature programs.** Most of the careful deployments in this space run a hybrid model: bot handles the routine coordination labor at scale; licensed case managers handle the human-judgment work, the complex escalations, and the cases that need a relationship. <!-- TODO: verify; the hybrid bot-and-case-manager deployment pattern is well-documented in operational case studies from major health systems and payers; specific staffing ratios and outcomes vary --> The case-manager-to-patient ratio achievable with bot support is meaningfully higher than without.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle care coordination well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to care coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve open items, retrieve appointment slots, schedule appointments, place referrals, check eligibility, submit refill requests, retrieve plan benefits, route prior-auth questions, log SDoH screens, escalate to case manager, surface crisis resources, and record events. Grounding and citation discipline are non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is a real question with mature options.** Several mature commercial vendors offer care-coordination AI products at major-payer and major-health-system scale, with EHR integration, eligibility integration, pharmacy integration, scheduling integration, case-management integration, and licensed-case-manager workforces. Most institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin-orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for specific capabilities (eligibility checks, prior-auth tracking, transportation benefits), and integrate with the institution's care-management, telehealth, and clinical-record infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
